### Anonymous Functions (Lambdas)

Lambda functions (also called anonymous functions) are functions without a name. They are useful for short, one-time operations.

```dart
void main() {
  // Lambda assigned to variable
  var add = (int a, int b) => a + b;
  print(add(3, 4)); // 7

  // Lambda with block body
  var multiply = (int a, int b) {
    return a * b;
  };
  print(multiply(3, 4)); // 12
}
```

### Lambda with Collections

Lambdas are commonly used with collection methods.

```dart
void main() {
  var numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

  // Using lambda with forEach
  numbers.forEach((n) => print(n * 2));

  // Using lambda with map
  var doubled = numbers.map((n) => n * 2).toList();
  print(doubled); // [2, 4, 6, 8, 10]

  // Using lambda with where (filter)
  var evens = numbers.where((n) => n % 2 == 0).toList();
  print(evens); // [2, 4]

  // Using lambda with reduce
  var sum = numbers.reduce((a, b) => a + b);
  print(sum); // 15
}
```

### Lambda Syntax Variations

| Syntax | Description | Example |
|--------|-------------|---------|
| `(p) => expr` | Single expression | `(x) => x * 2` |
| `(p) { ... }` | Block body with return | `(x) { return x * 2; }` |
| `(p1, p2) => expr` | Multiple params | `(a, b) => a + b` |
| `() => expr` | No params | `() => 42` |
| `(_) => expr` | Ignored param | `(_) => true` |

### Lambda as Function Argument

```dart
void main() {
  List<String> names = ['Charlie', 'Alice', 'Bob'];

  // Sort with lambda
  names.sort((a, b) => a.compareTo(b));
  print(names); // [Alice, Bob, Charlie]

  // Custom sort by length
  names.sort((a, b) => a.length.compareTo(b.length));
  print(names); // [Bob, Alice, Charlie]
}
```

> **Key Point:** Lambda functions use `=>` for single expressions and `{}` for multiple statements. They are first-class citizens - you can assign them to variables and pass them as arguments.

